Ileana Garnand

title: George W. Bush Presidential Library: Records on U.S.-Estonian Coordination for Georgian Cyber Defense (August 2008)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting access to records maintained by the National Security Council (NSC) and the Office of the National Security Advisor created between August 8, 2008, and December 31, 2008.

Specifically, I am seeking records concerning the coordination between the United States, the Government of Estonia, and the Government of Georgia regarding the transfer, implementation, or advising of Cyber-Defense Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs) during and immediately following the Russo-Georgian War.

Responsive records should include but not be limited to:

Diplomatic Cables and Memos: Communications between the White House and the U.S. Embassy in Tallinn regarding Estonian "Computer Emergency Response Team" (CERT-EE) deployments or technical assistance to Georgia.

NSC "Summaries of Conclusions": Records of meetings where the "cyber alliance" or technical cooperation between Estonia and Georgia was discussed, particularly concerning the mitigation of Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks attributed to the Russian Business Network (RBN) or other entities assumed to be formally or informally affiliated with the Russian state. 

Policy Guidance: Records related to the "provision of advice on cyber defense issues" as noted in the NATO-Georgia Commission framework established in late August 2008.

I request that the agency apply the "Foreseeable Harm" standard as codified in the FOIA Improvement Act of 2016. Given that these records are nearly 18 years old and concern a historical conflict involving a now-defunct criminal network (RBN), the disclosure of high-level policy coordination would not reasonably harm current national security. Please provide all reasonably segregable, non-exempt portions of responsive records, particularly those relating to public-facing diplomatic cooperation and general policy frameworks.

Keyword Search Appendix. Please conduct a categorical search for the following keywords:

Terms: "CERT-EE", "Estonian Informatics Centre", "Katrin Pärgmie", "Hillar Tork", "Cyber-Alliance", "TTP Transfer", "Tallinn Manual Precedents", "Information Blockade", "NATO-Georgia Commission".

Technical Identifiers: "AS40898", "BGP Hijacking", "Tbilisi Traffic Re-routing", "Tulip Systems coordination", "Tulix Systems coordination", "https://tulix.com/"

Section: Targeted Personnel and Offices

Please include in your search a categorical search for the records, calendars, and electronic communications of the following individuals and their respective staff during the August–September 2008 timeframe:

Melissa Hathaway: Senior Advisor to the Director of National Intelligence (DNI) and Director of the Joint Interagency Cyber Task Force. Hathaway was the primary architect of the CNCI and a key bridge between the intelligence community and the NSC.

Daniel Price: Deputy National Security Advisor for International Economic Affairs. Price was the lead on many G8 and international policy coordination issues during the Georgia crisis.

James Jeffrey: Deputy National Security Advisor. Jeffrey was heavily involved in the day-to-day management of the Georgia-Russia conflict.

Melanie Anne Gerber: Director for Cybersecurity on the National Security Council staff (2007–2009). She was a central node for interagency cyber policy.

Stephen Hadley: Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs (National Security Advisor).

Offices: The Directorate for Cybersecurity and Information Assurance and the Directorate for Central and Eastern European Affairs.

If certain parts of this request or certain portions must be redacted please provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed.

Thank you for the George W. Bush Presidential Library's commitment to transparency.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware

title: Bay Area Air Quality Management District: Air Permits and Toxic Air Contaminant Disclosures for Atomic Machines, Inc.

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Bay Area Air Quality Management District: Air Permits and Toxic Air Contaminant Disclosures for Atomic Machines, Inc.
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records for Atomic Machines, Inc. (Facility addresses: 950 Gilman St, Berkeley; 320 Martin Avenue, Santa Clara and, possibly, 5835 Doyle St, Emeryville, CA; ) regarding:

Permits to Operate (P/O): All current and historical permits for equipment including, but not limited to, clean room scrubbers, chemical vapor deposition (CVD) tools, and plasma etchers.

Health Risk Assessments (HRA): Any HRAs conducted to determine the impact of toxic air contaminants (TACs) on the surrounding residential or commercial community.

Emission Inventories: Annual reports detailing the quantity of criteria pollutants and precursor organic compounds (POCs) emitted.

Source Test Results: Data from any required testing of emission control systems (scrubbers/abatement tools).

According to their website, Atomic Machines (https://www.atomicmachines.com) is, "developing a completely new micro-manufacturing technology stack that will enable new classes of microdevices unattainable with existing semiconductor-based MEMS manufacturing technology." This is a very opaque company that was just awarded 15,000,000 in tax brakes. 

If certain parts of this request or certain portions must be redacted please provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed.

Thank you to the Bay Area Air Quality Management District's for the district's commitment to transparency. I look forward to working together on resolving this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware
